message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "Ha" HAJIMEMASHITE（Nice to meet you)　#nihongo　#aisatsu
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「は」じめまして
 
"Hajimemashite（はじめまして）"！
This is the very first Japanese phrase you may hear when you meet a person for the first time, which comes with bowing (Ojigi, おじぎ）.
 
As many of you may be familiar with movies, "Ojigi" plays a very important role in greeting, instead of handshaking. Bowing in Japan has many functions. Besides greeting, it may be used to express the feeling of respect, thanking, apologizing, and so on. 
 
For example, you can bow when saying "Hajimemashite", "Arigato (thank you)", "Gomen (sorry)", "Konnichiwa (hello)", "Sayonara (good bye)", "Omedeto (congratulations)", "Sumimasen (excuse me)",  and more.
 
Why don't you try one of "Ojigi" today? 
Have a lovely day/night, everyone!　*bow bow bow*
 
「はじめまして」…は、きっと初めて会った人から聞く最初の単語かもしれません。もちろん「おじぎ」つきで。

日本人は、習慣として様々な場面で「おじぎ」をします。
あいさつの他にも、感謝するとき、謝るとき、本当にいろいろ。

今日ひとつ、試してみてはどうですか？m(_ _ )m（おじぎ）

message.text:
Special congratulations to the Recipients of The Japan Foundation Awards 2014!!
第42回 国際交流基金賞 授賞式！受賞者の皆様、おめでとうございます！
http://www.jpf.go.jp/e/about/award/index.html

Every year since 1973, the Japan Foundation has presented the Japan Foundation Awards to individuals and organizations that have made significant contributions to promoting international mutual understanding and friendship between Japan and other countries through academic, artistic and other cultural pursuits. This year marks the 42nd year of the awards.

The Recipients for 2014 are as follows:
今年の受賞者はこちら：

・Mr. Sankyo Yanagiya (Rakugo Performer)[Japan]
　柳家さん喬 氏（落語家）[日本]
  http://www.jpf.go.jp/e/about/award/14/index.html#a
・Prof. Peter Drysdale (Professor Emeritus, Australian National University) [Australia]
　ピーター・ドライスデール 教授（オーストラリア国立大学名誉教授）[オーストラリア]
  http://www.jpf.go.jp/e/about/award/14/index.html#b
・Japanese Philology Department, Institute of Asian and African Studies, Lomonosov Moscow State University [Russia]
　モスクワ国立大学付属アジア・アフリカ諸国大学日本語学科[ロシア]
  http://www.jpf.go.jp/e/about/award/archive.html

#柳家さん喬　#落語　#日本研究　#日本語

message.text:
Happy  Friday night before the long weekend!

In Japan, the second Monday of October, this coming Monday 13th this year, is "Taiiku-no-Hi（たいいくのひ、体育の日）", or Sports Day, a national holiday to foster healthy minds and bodies through physical activity.

"Taiiku-no-Hi" was originally October 10th which was established to commemorate the 1964 Olympic Games in Tokyo, but it has been changed to the second Monday of the month.

You may wonder, why the Summer Olympic Game was held in October...It is said that one of the reasons was the weather to accommodate athletes from both warm countries and cold countries.

Why don't you exercise on this ”Taiiku-no-Hi”....aiming for 2020 Tokyo Olympic & Paralympic?? It is only six years away!

来週月曜日（13日）は祝日「体育の日」です！

10月第2月曜日は、毎年「体育の日」という祝日です。
この日は、「スポーツにしたしみ、健康な心身をつちかう」ことを目的にしていますが、実は1964年に東京で行われたオリンピックの開会式を記念して作られたって知っていましたか？

次に日本で行われるオリンピック・パラリンピックは2020年。もう６年しかない！

来週の体育の日は、オリンピックを目指して運動してみませんか！？
Have a nice "Taiiku-no-Hi"!!!

http://eng.nihongodecarenavi.jp/jpn/entry_4462.html
